    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-12-15T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-12-15T11:00:00-05:00" n="897"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d897">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.94114A/209: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Switzerland</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harrison</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bern</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-12-15T17:00:00+01:00"
                            >December 15, 1943—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 8:29 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>7871. American interests Japan and occupied territory, inspection of prisoner of
                    war camps. Foreign Office official handed Tait<note n="94" xml:id="d897fn94"
                        >George Tait, First Secretary of Legation in Switzerland.</note> December 14
                    notice to the effect that Gorgé reports full accounts Japanese prisoner camps
                    never visited and certain others for example those Tokyo and Yokohama have not
                    been inspected for more than a year. This situation greatly concerns Gorgé who
                    does not miss single opportunity personally insist with Japanese Foreign Office
                    obtain necessary authorization visit. He fears prisoners of war have impression
                    he is not doing all possible being [<hi rend="italic">bring?</hi>] moral comfort
                    which they doubtlessly need greatly.</p>
                <p>Under these circumstances he suggests British and American Governments again
                    insist authorization visit prisoners of war camps be given Swiss
                    representatives.</p>
                <p>British Legation received similar communication December 10 and telegraphed
                    London same day.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harrison</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
